  "prompt": "What is covered and uncovered interest parity?",
  "response": "Covered and uncovered interest parity are theories related to the relationship between interest rates and exchange rates in international finance.\n\n**Covered Interest Parity (CIP):**\nCovered Interest Parity refers to a condition where the difference in interest rates between two countries is equal to the difference between the forward exchange rate and the spot exchange rate. The forward rate is locked in through a forward contract, hence the trade is \"covered\" and eliminates exchange rate risk.\n\nThe formula for CIP can be written as:\n\\[ (1 + i_d) = \\frac{F}{S} (1 + i_f) \\]\nWhere:\n- \\( i_d \\) = domestic interest rate\n- \\( i_f \\) = foreign interest rate\n- \\( F \\) = forward exchange rate\n- \\( S \\) = spot exchange rate\n\nIf CIP holds, there are no arbitrage opportunities to earn risk-free profit from differences in interest rates and exchange rates.\n\n**Uncovered Interest Parity (UIP):**\nUncovered Interest Parity refers to the condition where the difference in nominal interest rates between two countries equals the expected depreciation or appreciation of their exchange rates. Unlike CIP, UIP does not involve hedging or using forward contracts, thus it is \"uncovered\" and involves exchange rate risk.\n\nThe formula for UIP can be written as:\n\\[ (1 + i_d) = E\\left( \\frac{S_{t+1}}{S_t} \\right) (1 + i_f) \\]\nWhere:\n- \\( E\\left( \\frac{S_{t+1}}{S_t} \\right) \\) = expected future spot exchange rate relative to the current spot exchange rate\n\nIn theory, if UIP holds, investors cannot earn an arbitrage profit based on differences in interest rates and expected future exchange rates.\n\nTo summarize:\n- **CIP involves** using forward contracts to hedge against exchange rate risk, ensuring no arbitrage opportunities.\n- **UIP involves** expectations about future exchange rates without hedging, potentially exposing investors to exchange rate risk.",
